European inflation on food slips
Accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid growth of food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in the 13 countries of the eurozone, with an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, the EU’s Luxembourg statistical office reported.
The official forecast was only 3% likely, Bloomberg said.
The European Central Bank (ECB) has not cut the base rate, other than the US central banks in the United Kingdom and Canada, saying that the reduction, along with rising raw material prices and easing unemployment, would lead to the development of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below two percent, but close to that.
According to one analyst, the ECB is trapped in the twenty-second-two: “we need to talk about inflation” so that it does not have to act on this issue later.
In Germany, the 3.3% record in November’s inflation is a twelve-year record, rising to 4.1 in Spain from 3.6.
Eurozone inflation has been high in rising food and energy prices.
The price of wheat has risen by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans has reached its highest level since 1973.
Oil and dairy products were also paid significantly more in 2007.
The world market price of stone oil has risen by 52 percent this year, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost 100 dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 percent this year to 2.5 percent in 2008, but will fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
According to the analysts, the 12-month inflation rate will remain at around 3 percent in the next 3-4 months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, it is expected that the ECB has lowered interest rates twice in 2008.
