In many places, they save on disinfectants
This year, more than 1,000 infections have been reported in hospitals, mainly due to the inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The sanitation conditions of hospitals, the congestion of the beds and the overload of staff are not favorable for stopping infections, according to the head of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many places, they also save on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
A man who was injected after a serious accident was diagnosed with antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
The patient was isolated.
There was a similar infection at the beginning of the year.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly thereafter he had to return with an MRSA infection, and an important operation has not been performed since then due to the bacteria in his body.
By 10 December this year, 1094 hospital infections caused by multi-suspensive pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, head of department at the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that so many multi-resistant pathogens have been reported in hospitals, and the rest are not known.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria are carried by one-third of people in their nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. pharyngitis, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be cured well.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or not properly, the bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develops a highly resistant bacteria that are resistant to antibiotics, which spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
In the case of temporary or persistent malfunction of the immune system, it can cause serious hospital infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning in degraded, elderly or low-weight patients in de minimisation.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about the MRSA infection, such infections belong to the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not investigated.
Resistant to antibiotics
“We areoling such patients, the nursing staff treats the patient in rubber gloves and masks, and they have the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are already examined to see if MRSA is present in their body, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current hospital conditions and conditions in Hungary are not favourable for the prevention of the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients incoming patients and immediately segregate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these studies.
Most cases will come to light if the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, the chief medical officer of the epidemiology center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
It is necessary to make antibiotic therapy targeted, i.e. microbiological studies should be carried out so that there is no resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always observe this.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA most often spreads from one patient to another by mediating medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in this in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by droplet infection and contact, but in the domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, the wards are often crowded, often the beds are very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, it is also happening, said Karolina Böröcz, that in hospitals in unfavorable financial situation, disinfectants are spared, there are few nurses, there are a lot of patients, so they are even more likely to develop infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are observed, there are demonstrably fewer such infections or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection causes huge costs for health insurers, so they fight it everywhere.
In England, for example, the government included the prevention and reduction of MRSA prevention and occurrence.
The program seems to be successful, and according to the data provided, MRSA infections are showing a downward trend in England.
One of the priorities of the European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) includes the development of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of such pathogens caused by hospital infections.
