Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meeting of experts will be completed on Tuesday, and on Wednesday, following the official opening ceremony, the negotiations of the international climate regime after the ministers will continue with the negotiations of the ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts to reduce emissions under the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
This is currently being debated between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also indicated that it does not currently intend to negotiate exact figures, although it is inclined to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
Another big question at the conference is whether developed countries undertake, in addition to reducing emissions, to provide both financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on subsidies to developing countries.
The funding fund, which is provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, expected within the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF).
6% of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Water Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its flagship role in global climate protection efforts and to facilitate the establishment of a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU will undertake to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent compared to 1990 levels by 2020, regardless of the success of the conclusion of the “post-2012 agreement” and is ready to undertake a reduction of up to 30 per cent if other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are willing to assume commitments appropriate to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that in 1997 the countries joining the Kyoto Protocol set a total target of a 5.2 percent reduction, within which the EU – then 15 member states – assumed minus 8 percent.
The Hungarian obligation is 6 percent greenhouse gas emission reduction compared to the period 1985-87, which Hungary will meet, the Ministry of Environment recalls in a press release.
The stakes in Bali are high, as the long-term international climate policy agreement must be concluded within two years, otherwise its entry into force would surely be postponed after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by another international emission reduction system, which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the International Scientific Panel on Climate Change, which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the UN Nobel Peace Prize-winning international scientific body on climate change.
This would result in a delay in reducing emissions and an unavoidable increase in the Earth’s average temperature above 2 degrees of Celcius, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
