Political Capital: the Hungarian Guard increased the country’s risk
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August this year with the support of the Jobbik Movement for a Better Hungary, increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital.
In its “risk warning”, the company wrote that the biggest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that “with the escalation of ethnic tensions between the already existing ethnic tension between the Hungarian Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations, even in the short term, violent ethnic clashes may develop”.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to be aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
As they wrote, all this can be traced back to one of the main omissions of Hungarian political actors: “the public debate on the Roma issue was handed over to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy for the Roma-Hungarian conflict”.
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard “caused the great domestic and international media attention, it has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of the country’s stability and democratic development”.
They recall that from the autumn of 2006 onwards, part of the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which received increasing publicity and impetus, has been transformed into more and more publicity and far-right extremist groups, that from the summer of 2007 several organisations, which calls itself a “national self-defense” association, have been established in Hungary.
“The common feature of these groups is to define themselves as an NGO, while openly proclaiming the preparation of their members, including armed, for defence (disaster protection, defence, law enforcement) tasks, moreover, citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, i.e. the state,” they added.
They noted that all this is done in accordance with the method that seeks to put various political aspirations into a civil guise based on the anti-political and anti-party nature of society.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association are therefore not only used to avoid legal pitfalls in these associations, but also to avoid legal pitfalls in the case of civil society.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor for neighbourhood relations.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard is a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, and the ultranationalist political actors of some neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy on the grounds of the establishment of the Hungarian Guard.
This has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he added.
According to the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, so political risks have increased for the region as a whole.
The operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar, for example, to the activities of the Bulgarian National Guard, the establishment of which was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The Bulgarian guard’s formation is due to the mass Roma riots that broke out in a quarter of Sofia (Kracna Poljana).
BNU took advantage of this to decide on the establishment of the guards, saying that the organization’s goal is “national self-defense”.
