A Khartoum court sentenced the British teacher to 15 days in prison and expulsion from the country in Sudan on Thursday evening for violating Islam, his lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of allowing her 6- to 7-year-old students to name a teddy bear as Muhammad. Islam, however, forbids any representation of its prophet.
Such an act can be punished by a whipping.
The 54-year-old British woman, a teacher at Unity High School in Khartoum, was arrested on Sunday in her apartment. Under Section 125 of the Sudan Penal Code, he was accused of insulting Islam and rebellion after the students’ parents repeatedly complained to him by the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story began in September, when the teacher asked his students, 6-7, to choose a name for the class’s teddy bear.
“The children proposed a total of eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” said Robert Boulos, the school’s principal.
In the end, 20 out of 23 children chose the first name Muhammad.
Of course, Muhammad is the name of the prophet Islam, but it is also a very common first name in Sudan.
The children then made a joint diary with the teddy bear’s photo and the inscription “My name is Muhammad.”
The bear itself was not labeled with that name. Rather, the problem lies in the fact that any representation of the prophet is a violation of Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues at the same school said she knew her well and that the teacher would never have done anything that would offend any religious beliefs. He said it was just an “innocent mistake”: “I only regret that he had the children vote for the name.”
Many students of the teacher agree with this opinion. According to them, the teacher "treats very well with the children" and "never speaks of religion in the class".
Let’s not forget that Muhammad is the second most popular first name in Britain, and there are 14 different spellings in English.
This first name, so often chosen by Muslim families, is a way of expressing respect for the prophet. (The firstborn child of the family receives this name.)
But what are the rules for using the first name?
Can you get this name, for example, a game?
This is obviously a matter of interpretation.
