Depressing Memories
After more than 60 years of encryption, the Bad Arolsen archive, which documents the fate of the 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime, has become public.
The 47 million archive documents, which occupy a 27-kilometre range of shelves in Bad Arolsen, in the province of Hessen, have so far only been researched for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. only provided a unique and name-related access to the former victims or their descendants.
The eleven states responsible for the treatment of the archives, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to open the archives to researchers and historians.
After all states ratified the Convention, the archives were opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the archives of Bad Arolsen will allow historians to conduct “research on the relocation of imprisoned people, the residents of the camps and the health of forced laborers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the publicization of the documents, as they contain names and thus confidential information.
This could include, for example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deported victims.
Lists of concentration camps and arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo began to be collected for practical reasons after the war. The aim was to find civilians who had been deported or forced to work on the basis of these, and to provide evidence of their internment, on the basis of which they could receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are currently engaged in the processing of tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, some of the scientific community does not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of paramount importance.
“These documents basically contain nothing new,” said Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Anti-Semitist Research at the Technical University of Berlin in 2006.
